      "message": "Yeah I really want to say\n    SkASSERT(!dstArray implies numGlyphs \u003d\u003d 0)\nwhich (since we don\u0027t have an \u0027imp\u0027 operator) turns into\n    SkASSERT(dstArray || numGlyphs \u003d\u003d 0)\nit also has the nice property of logically short circuiting, though that\u0027s a bit silly here.\n\nSince it seems \u0027imp\u0027 is A?B:true this could be written\n    SkASSERT(!dstArray ? numGlyphs \u003d\u003d 0 : true);\nWhich leads me to believe that in C++ the implies operator should be written `a??b` which is a binary operator which works like `a?b:true`. The objection would be that the ?? logical operator could have no ? binary operator, but whatever.\n\nBut that extra hanging true to make it work is ugly, could be\n    constexpr bool implies(bool a, bool b) { return a ? b : true; }\n    SkASSERT(implies(!dstArray, numGlyphs \u003d\u003d 0));\nThough without the infix of implies that looks a bit awkward. \n\nOf course, since it\u0027s the hanging `else true` that\u0027s ugly we end up with\n    if (!dstArray) { SkASSERT(numGlyphs \u003d\u003d 0); }",
